
TY  - JOUR
T1  - Vacancy Chains
AU  - Elsby, Michael W. L.
AU  - Gottfries, Axel
AU  - Michaels, Ryan
AU  - Ratner, David
Y1  - 2025/06/17
PY  - 2025
DA  - 2025/11/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/737234
DO  - 10.1086/737234
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 3550
EP  - 3604
VL  - 133
IS  - 11
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - Replacement hiring plays a central role in establishment dynamics. US establishments frequently report no net change in their employment, often for years, despite facing substantial gross turnover. We devise a tractable model in which replacement hiring is driven by a novel structure of frictions, combining firm dynamics, on-the-job search, and investments into job creation that are sunk at the point of replacement. A key implication is the emergence of vacancy chains. Quantitatively, the model reconciles the incidence of replacement hiring with large cross-establishment dispersion in labor productivity and largely replicates the volatility and persistence of job creation and unemployment.
AB  - Replacement hiring plays a central role in establishment dynamics. US establishments frequently report no net change in their employment, often for years, despite facing substantial gross turnover. We devise a tractable model in which replacement hiring is driven by a novel structure of frictions, combining firm dynamics, on-the-job search, and investments into job creation that are sunk at the point of replacement. A key implication is the emergence of vacancy chains. Quantitatively, the model reconciles the incidence of replacement hiring with large cross-establishment dispersion in labor productivity and largely replicates the volatility and persistence of job creation and unemployment.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/737234
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/737234
Y2  - 2026/04/24
